diff:1618997335:1618997335:=1,40d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Expansion: Indian Intonation%0a%3c :Author: EthanW%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.IndianAccentInTVShows|IndianAccentInTVShows]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.Spencer_L|Spencer_L]]%0a%3c :Section: E%0a%3c :Completed: 21.04.2021 - 02:28%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c I agree with you that Indian accent in TV shows is usually used for comedic effects. In addition to using phonemes that are characteristic in Indian languages (in particular Hindi), comedians also mimic the Indian intonation very often. Because at phonological level many other languages do not have alveolar plosives [d] and [t] or have retroflex flap [ɽ] just as Hindi, in my opinion using Indian intonation plays greater role in reinforcing stereotypes of Indian accent and even the language speakers. %0a%3c %0a%3c For those who are interested in Indian intonation, please refer to this paper for more details: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281600861_The_intonation_of_Indian_languages_An_areal_phenomenon%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
